Results: 
Most of these injuries involved the subaxial cervical spine between C5 and C7. In all, 41.2% of AS patients were considered to be ASIA A, whereas 44.4% of DISH patients were classified as ASIA E. Surgery was performed in 83.3% of AS patients and 66.7% of DISH patients, and the overall complication rates were 41.7% and 33.3%, respectively. There were no statistically significant differences between the survivorship and outcomes of the AS and DISH groups and 81.3% of all respondents were classified as having excellent or good outcomes. There were 4 deaths, all of which were considered to be related to the use of halo-vest immobilization.
